      <text>Gauss-Jordan Method for Matrix Inversion</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Use the Gauss-Jordan method (row operations) to find the inverse of \[ {@A@} \]&nbsp;</p><p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3><b>Worked solution</b></h3>
<p>This question asked you to find the inverse using the Gauss-Jordan method (row operations). To use the Gauss-Jordan method set up the problem as \[ \left[ A \big{|} I \right] \] and then use row operations to reduce this to reduced row echelon form.&nbsp; The left hand side will be the identity matrix, and overall we will have&nbsp;\[ \left[ I \big{|} A^{-1} \right]. \]
So, using our values we have \[ {@ws1@}\] which has reduced row echelon form (working omitted) \[ {@ws2@}\] from which we read out the inverse as \[ {@ta@}.\]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
